{{Copy to Wiktionary}}'''''Frig''''' ({{IPAc-en|f|r|ɪ|ɡ}}){{sfn|Allied Chambers|1999|p=533}} is an [[interjection]] in the [[English language]] that expresses [[contempt]].{{sfn|Witte|2012|p=82}} The word can be used as a [[euphemism]] for ''[[fuck]]'' or to refer to [[masturbation]] or [[sexual intercourse]].{{sfn|Sheidlower|2009|p=59}} The [[participle]] form ''frigging'' is used as an [[adjective]] to express [[annoyance]] or [[frustration]].{{sfn|Hughes|2015|p=186}} Oxford University Press' ''Oxford Dictionary of Modern Slang'' argues that ''frig'' originally meant ''to move restlessly''.{{sfn|Ayto & Simpson|2010|p=99}} A different [[etymology]] is proposed by Oxford University Press' ''Dictionary of Euphemisms'', which argues that ''frig'' initially meant ''to rub'' and developed its sexual meanings from this origin; this dictionary further argues that the modern meanings of the word are not derived from the [[Cornish language|Cornish word]] ''frig'', meaning ''wife'', or from the [[List of Germanic deities|Germanic deity]] [[Frigg]], the wife of [[Odin]][{conjecture}].{{sfn|Holder|2008|p=189}} The deity Frigg has sometimes been referred to in recent times as "Friga" or "Frigga" in order to distance her from the English word ''frig''.{{sfn|Sheard|2011|p=238}} The word's use as a synonym for ''masturbate''[extracted from frig-same route meaning] dates to 1598 in the United Kingdom, while its use as a euphemism for ''fuck'' dates to 1879 in the United Kingdom.{{sfn|Dalzell & Victor|2014|p=322}} In 1892, the word was subtly included in [[Joseph Wright (linguist)|Joseph Wright]]'s glossary of the dialect of the Yorkshire village of [[Windhill]], with the Latin definition ''coire''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wright |first=Joseph |date=1892 |title=A Grammar of the Dialect of Windhill in the West Riding of Yorkshire. Illustrated by a series of dialect specimens, phonetically rendered; with a glossarial index of the words used in the grammar and specimens |url=https://archive.org/stream/grammarofdialect00wrigrich#page/226/mode/2up |location=London |publisher=Kegan Paul |page=226}}</ref> ''Frig'' has entered the [[Australian English]] [[lexicon]].{{sfn|Miller|2015|p=72}} In the [[U.S. state]] of [[Maine]], ''frig'' does not have the sexual connotations that it has elsewhere, and has gained social acceptance in the phrase ''frig around'' meaning ''to fool around'' or ''to putter around''.{{sfn|Hendrickson|2000|p=225}}

==In popular culture==
*The word is used in the title of the bawdy [[drinking song]] "[[Good Ship Venus|Friggin' in the Riggin']]".

