Marathi furthermore contrasts {{ipa|/əi, əu/}} with {{ipa|/ai, au/}}.

There are two more vowels in Marathi to denote the pronunciations of English words such as of {{IPA|/æ/}} in ''act'' and {{IPA|/ɔ/}} in ''all''. These are written as {{angbr|अ‍ॅ}} and {{angbr|ऑ}}.

Marathi retains several features of Sanskrit that have been lost in north-Indian Sanskrit-based languages such as Hindi and Bengali, especially in terms of pronunciation of vowels and consonants. For instance, Marathi retains the original Sanskrit pronunciation of {{angbr|अं}} {{IPA|[əⁿ]}}, {{angbr|ऐ}} {{IPA|[əi]}}, and {{angbr|औ}} {{IPA|[əu]}}. However, as was done in Gujarati, Marathi speakers tend to pronounce ऋ {{IAST|ṛ}} somewhat similar to {{IPA|[ru]}}, unlike most other Indic languages which changed it to {{IPA|[ri]}} (e.g. the original Sanskrit pronunciation of the language's name was ''{{IAST|saṃskṛtam}}'', while in day-to-day Marathi and Gujarati it is ''{{IAST|saṃskrut}}''. In other Indic languages, it is closer to ''{{IAST|sanskrit}}''). Spoken Marathi allows for conservative stress patterns in words like राम (''rama'') with an emphasis on the ending vowel sound, a feature that has been lost in Hindi.

